07096nam a22008055i 9780231541787DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984688174  a97802315417877 a10.7312/gubr171522doi  a(DE-B1597)478173  a(OCoLC)951712095  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPSY0170002bisacsh04a36222300aReimagining the Human Service Relationship /ced. by Jaber Gubrium, Per Solvang, Tone Andreassen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I. The Human Service Relationship -- t1. From the Iron Cage to Everyday Life -- tPart II. Service User Perspectives -- t2. Professional Intervention from a Service User Perspective -- t3. Expertise and Ambivalence in User- Focused Human Ser vice Work -- t4. Flipping the Script -- t5. Service Users’ Negotiated Identity in a Social Enterprise and the Opportunity for Reflection in Action -- t6. Between Control and Surrender in Terminal Illness -- tPart III. Professional Work -- t7. New Relations Between “Professionals” and Disabled Service Users -- t8. The Use of Elder-Clowning to Foster Relational Citizenship in Dementia Care -- t9. Managing the Complexity of Family Contact in Child Welfare -- t10. Risk, Trust, and the Complex Sentiments of Enacting Care -- t11. “Civil Disobedience” and Conflicting Rationalities in Elderly Care -- tPart IV. Re imagined Service Relationships -- t12. Mental Health Self- Knowledge: Crossing Borders with Recovery Colleges and Tojisha Kenkyu -- t13. Tension and Balance in Teaching “The Patient Perspective” to Mental Health Professionals -- t14. Reimagining the Doctor– Patient Relationship -- t15. Who’s Who and Who Cares? Personal and Professional Identities in Welfare Services -- t16. Border Work: Negotiating Shifting Regimes of Power -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe traditional lines of demarcation between service providers and service users are shifting. Professionals in managed service organizations are working to incorporate the voices of service users into their missions and the way they function, and service users, with growing access to knowledge, have taken on the semblances of professional expertise. Additionally, the human services environment has been transformed by administrative imperatives. The drive toward greater efficiency and accountability has weakened the bond between users and providers.Reimagining the Human Service Relationship is informed by the premise that the helping relationship should be seen as developing in the interactive space between those who provide human services and those who receive them. The contributors to this volume redefine the contours, roles, institutional divisions, means, and aims of providing and receiving services in a range of settings, including child welfare, addiction treatment, social enterprise, doctoring, mental health, and palliative care. Though they advocate an experience-near approach, they remain sensitive to the ambiguities and competing rationalities of the service relationship. Taken together, these chapters reimagine the service relationship by making visible the working relevancies of service delivery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHuman services. 0aInterpersonal relations. 0aPhysician and patient. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Interpersonal Relations.2bisacsh1 aAndreassen, Tone Alm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndreassen, Tone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarnes, Marian, econtributor.4c